  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1626202204" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1626202204" />
    <a title="Shaun" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2621599-shaun"><img alt="Shaun" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1304973778p2/2621599.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1626202204?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shaun" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shaun" href="/user/show/2621599-shaun">Shaun</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780870113055" href="/book/show/533785.Almost_Transparent_Blue">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2621599-shaun?shelf=1001-books-to-read-before-dying">1001-books-to-read-before-dying</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2621599-shaun?shelf=modern-literature-existentialism">modern-literature-existentialism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1626202204" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4633537718915090235">What can be said about this peculiar little book that has not already been said by far more intelligent folks than your&apos;s truly?! Yes. It&apos;s a quick read. Yes. It&apos;s gritty with the details of drug abuse and sexual orgies &quot;[r]endered in excruciating, often repugnant detail.&quot; If you don&apos;t like either drug abuse and/or sexual conduct given in such &quot;repugnant detail&quot;, don&apos;t read it. If, however, you want an introduction to one of Japan&apos;s finest, post-modernism writers, then DO read this book. <br/><br/>I am go</span>
  <span id="freeText4633537718915090235" style="display:none">What can be said about this peculiar little book that has not already been said by far more intelligent folks than your's truly?! Yes. It's a quick read. Yes. It's gritty with the details of drug abuse and sexual orgies "[r]endered in excruciating, often repugnant detail." If you don't like either drug abuse and/or sexual conduct given in such "repugnant detail", don't read it. If, however, you want an introduction to one of Japan's finest, post-modernism writers, then DO read this book. <br /><br />I am going to quote heavily from University of Oxford doctoral candidate Bianca Jackson from Peter Boxall's amazing little big book, "1001 Books You Must Read Before You Die" (2010 ed) because it is so right on and righteous here.<br /><br />"Ryu Murakami's 'Almost Transparent Blue' describes the day-to-day existence of a group of nihilistic [and morally challenged] youths living near an American army base in an unnamed Japanese port town. The narrator, Ryu, and his friends have rejected the formulaic lifestyle of the 'straights' -- including job security, family, and most importantly, moral constraints. Rather, they devote their shared existence to drugs, sexual orgies, and music. Seemingly without a plot, the novel outlines the boredom, alienation, and subsequent depravity of a generation lacking purpose."<br /><br />Whew! That's calling it like it is. Even now some 40 years later nihilism and immorality seems to be running rampant. The questions arises: Why? Why have things gotten so far down the drain? Where, when and how did we lose our humanity? Was it during the Sixties? Or did it occur sooner during the Fifties? Forties? Thirties? Twenties? Or Teens of the early 20th Century right around the First World War?<br /><br />Okay, okay, I know I mentioned this one earlier, but I think a bit of Fernando Pessoa's "The Book of Disquiet" originally written around 1931 to 1934 but finally published in 1982 may help provide the answer: <br /><br />"Art gives us the illusion or liberation from the sordid business of being. Whilst (dig that word!) feeling the slings and arrows of Hamlet, prince of Denmark, we do not feel our own, which are base because they are ours and because they are in themselves base." Huh? A bit of a tautological reasoning there. <br /><br />But the Maestro goes on and states, "Love, sleep, drugs and intoxicants are elementary forms of art or rather elementary forms of producing the same effect as art. But love, sleep, and drugs all bring with them their own disappointments. One grows sated or disillusioned with love. We wake from sleep and whilst (there it is, again!) we slept, we did not live. The price of drugs is the ruin of every body they were used to stimulate. But there is no disillusion in art because its illusory nature is clear from the start. One does not wake from art because, although we dream it, we are not asleep. There is no tribute or fine to pay for having enjoyed art. Since in some way it is not ours, we do not have to pay for or repent from the pleasure it offers us. ... To possess something is to lose it. To feel something without possessing it is to keep it, because in that way one extracts its essence." No. 256 [518] from "The Book of Disquiet" (Serpent's Tail Publishers) (1991, 2010 ed). Now back to Bianca.<br /><br />"Written when he was only twenty-three, Ryu Murakami's 'Almost Transparent Blue' refuses to spare the reader's sensibilities. The audience is forced to partake in a catalog of graphic sexual violence and drug-induced frenzies, unable to avert its gaze from the unpalatable. But beneath the meticulous descriptions of the grotesque is a stark portrait of a universal loneliness, reminiscent of Albert Camus or Franz Kafka. Straying away from the introspective trend of postwar literature, this enfant terrible of the Japanese art world (I presume she means Ryu here and not just this book itself) annihilates the Japan of snowcapped mountains and cherry blossoms, exposing the underbelly of a culture in flux. Dividing readers and critics alike, 'Almost Transparent Blue' won the prestigious Akutagawa Literary Prize in 1976, and became an instant bestseller." <br /><br />Personally, an earlier Japanese author -- Yukio Mishima -- was "[s]traying away from the introspective trend of postwar literature" annihilating those precious Japanese "snowcapped mountains and cherry blossoms [and] exposing the underbelly of a culture in flux" in such works as "The Sound of Waves" and his four (4) volume work "The Sea of Fertility". But there's no denying this little beauty does it far less subtlety and far more crudely "in your face" than does Mishima's work.<br /><br />Time to avoid considering "the slings and arrows" of my own base nature and go engage in more coolish escapism reading some Russian existentialism and post-modernism literature. Yes, 'tis a rockin' good reading life after all!</span>
  <a data-text-id="4633537718915090235" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


