    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1786328902" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1786328902" />
    <a title="Griffin Alexander" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25982974-griffin-alexander"><img alt="Griffin Alexander" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1522817332p2/25982974.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1786328902?book_show_action=true">Oct 17, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Griffin Alexander" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Griffin Alexander" href="/user/show/25982974-griffin-alexander">Griffin Alexander</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1786328902" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5167188825070822456">A bleak portrayal of a defeated country&apos;s youth culture that both consumes American (counter-) culture and is consumed by it. In defiance against the established order of madness that led Japan to a Pyrrhic defeat at the hands of the Allies, the youth here are afloat in their own existence against their cultural inheritance, but with no substantive alternative—suicide here is merely gestural and holds none of the symbolic or existential weight that it is given by the likes of Mishima/Kawabata/Ak</span>
  <span id="freeText5167188825070822456" style="display:none">A bleak portrayal of a defeated country's youth culture that both consumes American (counter-) culture and is consumed by it. In defiance against the established order of madness that led Japan to a Pyrrhic defeat at the hands of the Allies, the youth here are afloat in their own existence against their cultural inheritance, but with no substantive alternative—suicide here is merely gestural and holds none of the symbolic or existential weight that it is given by the likes of Mishima/Kawabata/Akutagawa etc. in Japan's literary past. American imports stand in as the sole source of cultural interest and also source of extreme indifference as records interchangeably grace the turntable to little effect upon the listeners aside from demarcating the time expended and the names of various bands rattled off from LP covers.<br /><br />Despite the criticisms levied against it, this novel is not plotless—it is too short for that. There is a good deal of drinking/heroin/hash, a pretty sad drug/sex party with some GIs in which our narrator is sexually imposed upon (metaphorically and otherwise), a good long mescaline trip w/ revelations concerning the US military's colonization of Japanese consciousness, and finally a rock n roll concert where our ragtag group of junkie freaks beat the shit out of a guard—all leading to the disillusionment of the narrator and his self-harm and subsequent self-removal from this strange (and somehow very compelling) cycle of events. The chief reveal of this semi-cyclical structure is its portrayal of the willing subjection of youth to the project of absence sought in the transcendent painfulness of rough sex and heavy drug use. It is not a true desire for absence (as per the note on suicide above), but rather a desire for passive objectness, that is, what goes into both existing and interacting (even if that means being used by others in way that disregards your very existence as another and equal <i>subject</i>) without the need to make decisions, or inhabit action mindfully. <br /><br />Though this review may make <i>ATB</i> come off as a simple novelistic depiction of postwar anomie, Murakami actually makes it all rather compelling, surprisingly erotic (albeit with sublimation [when it happens] merely pointing away <i>from</i> boredom/ennui, rather than <i>toward</i> anything productive), and simultaneously disquieting—it is an interesting and uncommon trio to experience all at once. There is a certain pathos present that is missing from the more famous western examples like <i>Train Spotting</i> or <i>Naked Lunch</i>. Here the action never reaches the pitch of black humor or tongue-in-cheek proto-sci-fi-hallucinatory-commentary; rather, we simply have what is, this object of text, and that is perhaps what feels the strangest.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5167188825070822456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

